  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "whKMvcGHM5dU4TnFehn1jMBxn2Y=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Claim\n\nStamps used to back **feed writes** (manifests) should be created **mutable** \u2014 immutable stamps waste one bucket slot per feed update and will exhaust long before the nominal capacity.\n\n## Evidence\n\n- Each feed update is a new SOC \u2192 a new chunk that consumes a bucket slot under immutable semantics\n- With immutable batches, the batch fails when any single bucket fills (non-uniform distribution means this happens well before 2^depth chunks)\n- Mutable batches replace the oldest chunk in an overflowing bucket \u2014 old feed indices are garbage-collected automatically, keeping capacity stable\n\n## How\n\n```js\nbee.createPostageBatch(amount, depth, { immutableFlag: false })\n```\n\n## Why it matters\n\nOur adapter writes frequent manifest updates (every 3-second debounce flush). Running these on immutable stamps is a time-bomb: the batch eventually fails on hot-bucket exhaustion long before its TTL expires. Mutable stamps are the correct primitive for this workload.\n",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z"
    }
  },
